Introduction¶

In this tutorial, we will explore the entire data science pipeline. We will start with data collection and processing, leading into an explatory analysis, then hypothesis testing with machine learning. Finally we will finish our conclusion and main takeways from our analysis.

We have chosen to focus on Airline Customer Satisfaction. Airline companies want to maximize customer satisfaction to bolster company reputations in the hopes of improving business. However, there are thousands of airline customers and countless factors that can influence their satisfaction. Using data science, we are able to analyze large amounts of data to understand what influences customer satisfaction the most and how to improve on it. The information gathered from this data science process is highly valuable for not only airline companies but all companies who want to understand their customer base, build costumer loyalty, and how to best improve on their product.

This is an important topic in general because it can allow airlines to adjust their services based on what is most likely to make flyers satisfied. This promotes greater service, makes the industry more competitive, and will lead to better experiences overall. This is also an important topic in a data science context as it contains a very large dataset with many different types of data (categorical, numerical, etc.). This diverse dataset makes it a very interesting problem to try and develop recommendations and insights.

1. Data Collection / Processing¶

To look at airline costumer satisfaction, we must first find a database that contains airline specific information on a large quantity of costumers, such as loyalty, flight amenities, flight path information, etc. We decided to use a Kaggle dataset for this tutorial. The exact link to the dataset can be found at https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/raminhuseyn/airline-customer-satisfaction. In order to download the data, we selected the black download button in the top right which saves the file Airline_customer_satisfaction.

The dataset was downloaded in .csv format (in this tutorial, we simply named it data.csv). Using a csv file makes it easier for us to understand the data when looking at it and to process it with our tools. We will be using various Python libraries in a Juptyer notebook. We started our Jupyter Notebook in the same directory. To collect and process our data, we import the Python libraries pandas, which allows us to manipulate data, and numpy, which gives us tools to work with large, multi-dimensional datasets.

To learn how to install and setup jupyter notebook, you can use the following link: https://jupyter.org/install

Initial Observations¶

Above, we imported the csv and used the pandas module to read it and save it as "df". This represents a dataframe and is the way in which we organize our data. This structure has rows and columns which are easy to access. Additionally, we can perform operations on entire rows and filter by values, which we will see later in the tutorial. However, for now

We can immediately see that there are a number of columns in this dataset. The 'satisfaction' value is a binary classification of whether an individual was happy with their airline experience. The other columns contain various datatypes representing metrics associated with someone's experience with the airline. However, we can't tell from this whether there are missing values or portions of the data that are incomplete. Thus, we are going to run two important functions tell us the amount of entries for each column and the number of null values.

1) The first function we will run is df.info(). This tells us a summary of all columns, what type is stored in the column, and the number of non-null values. This is helpful in identifying rows that are missing values, as the counts will be different. 2) The second function we will run is df.isnull().sum(). This tells us how many null values are in a column, which helps us figure out parts of the data that need to be changed or dropped.

Cleaning Data¶

Based on the above, we can see the dataset is not as clean as we would like. Thus, we can take a couple steps before data analysis to make it easier for us. A usual issue with datasets is that there is missing data, represented as NaNs. Since our dataset is very large, we don't want to check every entry to see if there are any missing values, so we clean it up by dropping all the NaNs using dropna(). Then we will re-run the above functions to ensure that it works.

Model: Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, Machine Learning¶

Imports, Identify Features, Convert Categorical Features to Binary, Split into Training and Testing Set¶

Now that we have explored and visualized our data, we can create models and use machine learning to test our hypotheses about airline costumer satisfaction. The Python library we will be using is scikit-learn which gives us simple and efficient machine learning tools.

The goal in this analysis will be to develop a model to predict whether a customer will be satisfied or not given the other variables.

To build this model, we will have to partitition the dataset into a testing and training set. We will train the model and the score it based on its performance with the testing set.

In [15]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix


features = ['Flight Distance', 'Age', 'Departure Delay in Minutes', 'Arrival Delay in Minutes',
            'Customer Type', 'Type of Travel', 'Class']
X_full = df_cleaned[features]
Y_full = df_cleaned['satisfaction'] == 'satisfied'  # Converting to binary
X_full = pd.get_dummies(X_full)


# Split data into training and testing sets
X_train_full, X_test_full, Y_train_full, Y_test_full = train_test_split(X_full, Y_full, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

In the above code sample, after importing the necessary modules we split our data into four categories: x-training, x-testing, y-training, and y-testing. The test_size value shows that 0.2 or 20% of the data will be allocated for testing while the remaining data points will be used for training.

Model One: Logistic Regression¶

This model uses logistic regression for the prediction. The link to the full sklearn model can be found here: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.linear_model.LogisticRegression.html

To assess the model we are creating two charts:

1) A confusion matrix - this will show the correct labels versus the predicted labels for the dataset and indicate how the model classified them. We want to minimize the number of incorrect labels (false negatives and positives)

2) A scatterplot of predictions versus output - this will plot the points based on the predicted value and actual value

In [16]:
log_reg = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000)
log_reg.fit(X_train_full, Y_train_full)
log_reg_score = log_reg.score(X_test_full, Y_test_full)

print (f"Logistic Regression Accuracy: {log_reg_score:.2f}")

# Confusion Matrix
predictions = log_reg.predict(X_test_full)
cm = confusion_matrix(Y_test_full, predictions)
cm_display = sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, cmap='Blues', fmt='g', xticklabels=['Not Satisfied', 'Satisfied'], yticklabels=['Not Satisfied', 'Satisfied'])
plt.xlabel('Predicted Labels')
plt.ylabel('True Labels')
plt.title('Confusion Matrix for Logistic Regression')
plt.show()

# Scatter Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.scatter(log_reg.predict_proba(X_test_full)[:, 1], Y_test_full, alpha=0.5, color='blue')
plt.title('Predicted Probabilities vs. Actual Outcomes')
plt.xlabel('Predicted Probability of Satisfaction')
plt.ylabel('Actual Outcome')
plt.yticks([0, 1], ['Not Satisfied', 'Satisfied'])
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Logistic Regression Accuracy: 0.69

The accuracy of the model is 0.69 which is not extremely high. The confusion matrix shows that there are a lot of false negatives in the model. This indicates that this is not a very strong model and does a relatively poor job predicting the output. We can try to implement a different type of model and see whether we can improve upon this.

Model Two: KNN¶

This model will be the KNN or K-Nearest Neighbors classification. You can read the documentation for this at https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.neighbors.KNeighborsClassifier.html

In [25]:
best_k = 0
best_score = 0
for k in range(1, 21):
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    knn.fit(X_train_full, Y_train_full)
    k_score = knn.score(X_test_full, Y_test_full)
    if k_score > best_score:
        best_k = k
        best_score = k_score
    
print (f"KNN Best Accuracy: {best_score:.2f} at k={best_k}")

# Confusion Matrix
best_knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=best_k)
best_knn.fit(X_train_full, Y_train_full)
predictions = best_knn.predict(X_test_full)
cm = confusion_matrix(Y_test_full, predictions)
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, cmap='Blues', fmt='g', xticklabels=['Not Satisfied', 'Satisfied'], yticklabels=['Not Satisfied', 'Satisfied'])
plt.xlabel('Predicted Labels')
plt.ylabel('True Labels')
plt.title(f'Confusion Matrix for KNN with k={best_k}')
plt.show()

# Scatter Plot
try:
    probabilities = best_knn.predict_proba(X_test_full)[:, 1]
except AttributeError:
    probabilities = predictions
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.scatter(probabilities, Y_test_full, alpha=0.5, color='blue')
plt.title(f'KNN Predicted Probabilities vs. Actual Outcomes at k={best_k}')
plt.xlabel('Predicted Probability of Satisfaction')
plt.ylabel('Actual Outcome (1 for Satisfied, 0 for Not Satisfied)')
plt.yticks([0, 1], ['Not Satisfied', 'Satisfied'])
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

KNN Best Accuracy: 0.61 at k=18

This has a slightly lower accuracy at 0.61. The best accuracy was achieved at k=18. The correlation matrix shows more false positives than false negatives this time and the model did not perform that well overall. The scatterplot shows almost no distinction between the two groups. Based on this, the logistic regression model is a better model but neither of the models developed are extremely accurate.

Conclusion¶

Through this exploration we went through the full data science pipleline in order to try and gain insights from the dataset and learn more about what makes people satisfied with their airline. We began with data collection and cleaned it. Then we performed a lot of initial analysis and generated visualizations in order to learn more about the data. Finally, we built two different models and compared their results with a correlation matrix and a scatterplot. Based on the findings we would have to look into different models to recommend definitive changes as an airline as we were not able to achieve a very high accuracy. However, we can still indicate that some of the features we found to be significant in the exploratory data analysis, such as class and service aspects, have heavy correlation with their satisfaction and experience.
